OSX Keybindings:

All apps:
cmd+Q  -quit active app

Terminal,Chrome,Sublime Text
cmd+]   -cycle through next tabs
cmd+[   -cycle through previous tabs
cmd+T   -add new tab to current window
cmd+N   -open new window
opt+cmd+.    -close current tab
cmd+shift+W    -close current window

Additionally in Chrome:
opt+cmd+]  -navigate forward in history
opt+cmd+[  -navigate backward in history
cmd+R   -refresh page
cmd+L   -focus address bar and highlight text if any

Additionally in  Sublime Text:
fn+F5 -refresh folders
opt+cmd+/  -toggle comments for cursor line or multiline selection
opt+cmd+S   -save all
cmd+s -save
cmd+P -toggle search box
cmd+F -open find bar
cmd+shift+F -open find in files bar


To get these mappings :

For Terminal: map keys via OSX settings app
Select Net Tab ==> cmd+]
Select Previous Tab ==> cmd+[
Close Tab ==> opt+cmd+.

For Chrome: map keys via OSX settings app
Select Net Tab ==> cmd+]
Select Previous Tab ==> cmd+[
Close Tab ==> opt+cmd+.
Back ==> opt+cmd+[
Forward ===> opt+cmd+]

For Sublime: map keys via Sublime keymap overrides.
In Preferences > Key Bindings > User:
Change in sublime prefs from:
[
    { "keys": ["f5"], "command": "refresh_folder_list" },
    { "keys": ["super+]"], "command": "next_view" },
    { "keys": ["super+["], "command": "prev_view" },
    { "keys": ["alt+super+."], "command": "close" },
    { "keys": ["super+n"], "command": "new_window" },
    { "keys": ["super+t"], "command": "new_file" }
]

Note: Sublime keymap key name to OSX keyboard keyname conversions:
super == OSX
ctrl == ctrl
alt == opt


